{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The central question is 'How is man possible?'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Buber's answer is very important to the further development of his principle of dialogue in psychology (primarily his notion of confirmation) and philosophy of art, but it is not quite clear how compatible it is with some of his earlier theses from I and Thou.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "In particular, the relation between 'distance' and the I-It relation is unclear.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "There are two seemingly contradictory statements: 'In the beginning is the relation' and 'The primal distance is a presupposition of the relation'.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The aim of this paper is to examine these anthropological foundations and to elucidate this apparent contradiction.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Buber came to the insight that the principle of human life is twofold and is based on two movements.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "He calls the first of these two movements 'the primal setting at a distance' (Urdistanzierung) and the second of them 'entering into a relation' (In-Beziehung-Treten).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The first movement is the presupposition of the second.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "This results from the fact that 'one can enter into relation only with a being which has been set at a distance'.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The categories 'distance' and 'relationship' are implicit to each other, which means that 'the process of distancing implies as its complementary the process of entering into a relationship'.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The personal dimension of human life is constituted through the 'relation' and not through 'distance'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The first movement yields the answer to the question: 'How is man possible?' The second answers the question: 'How is human life realized?'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "The mutual confirmation of human beings in their uniqueness distinguishes man from other living beings.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Man is the sole living creature in whom the category of possibility is embodied—he is not fully determined and fixed in his being—and therefore needs confirmation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "A presupposition for both characteristics is the first movement of 'distance', which guarantees that another person is perceived as an independent counterpart.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "The confirmation itself then represents the realization of the second movement of the 'relation'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "The connection between 'entering into a relation' and the basic word I-Thou is obvious.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The 'relation' from the essay 'Distance and Relation' can be fully identified with the I-Thou relationship from I and Thou.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "The connection between 'primal distance' and the I-It relation is not so obvious.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "'Primal distance' is inherent to every man as a man; it is a particular state that establishes the human situation and as such is pre-personal.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "The relations of I-Thou and I-It express the personal existence of man.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "'Distance' makes room for entering into a relationship, but when the establishment of the I-Thou relation fails, the distance becomes solidified and thickened, thereby presenting an obstacle to the essential relationship.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "The process of distancing is a priori in the Kantian sense.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "In the concept of 'primal distance', that is the ontological presupposition of all human relationships to all existing beings, Buber recognized the anthropological foundation of his cosmic vision of dialogical life.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
